---
import ElevationLayout from '../../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../../components/elevation/Section.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '../../lib/products/registry';
import { productJsonLd } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const product = getProductBySlug('agent-restraint-specification')!;
const jsonLd = productJsonLd(product, 'https://evoked.dev/products/agent-restraint-specification');
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Agent Restraint Specification Template"
  description="Your agent can access more than you authorized. Define what it must refuse - boundary audit, refusal spec, accountability, adversarial testing. $49 PDF."
  structuredData={jsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Products", "Constraint architecture"]}
    headline="What should your agent refuse to do?"
    metaphor={["Your agent can access more than you authorized."]}
    sub="Most teams discover the answer in production. This template lets you specify it first."
  />

  <Section marker="FIG · I" heading="Four questions. Two minutes.">
    <p class="lede">Pick one agent in your system. Answer honestly.</p>

    <div class="pd-checks">
      <div class="pd-check">
        <span class="pd-check-number">1</span>
        <div class="pd-check-body">
          <p class="pd-check-question">Can your agent access data it does not need for its primary function?</p>
          <p class="pd-check-result">If yes - or if you are not sure - you have a boundary gap.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-check">
        <span class="pd-check-number">2</span>
        <div class="pd-check-body">
          <p class="pd-check-question">If your agent received a request that violated your values, would it refuse - or comply because the request was polite?</p>
          <p class="pd-check-result">If you are not sure - your agent has no refusal specification.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-check">
        <span class="pd-check-number">3</span>
        <div class="pd-check-body">
          <p class="pd-check-question">Are your agent's decisions logged in a way someone could review them tomorrow?</p>
          <p class="pd-check-result">If no - you have no accountability architecture.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-check">
        <span class="pd-check-number">4</span>
        <div class="pd-check-body">
          <p class="pd-check-question">Have you ever tested your agent with deliberately adversarial input?</p>
          <p class="pd-check-result">If never - your restraint specification is untested.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="pd-body">
      Those are your gaps. The template below helps you close them. If all four
      passed, use it to formalize and stress-test what you have.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · II" heading="This already happened">
    <p class="lede">
      During a routine self-audit, an autonomous agent discovered credit card
      credentials in the systems it could access. Another agent brute-forced a
      server - not out of malice, but because nobody had told it not to.
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      These were not security failures. They were specification failures. The
      agents had capability without boundaries. No one had written down what they
      should refuse to do.
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      Restraint is not a limitation on capability. It is the mechanism that makes
      trust architecturally real.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · III" heading="What the template covers">
    <div class="pd-pillars">
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">1</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Boundary audit</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">Map the gap between what your agent can access and what it was authorized to access. Most teams have never done this. The gaps will surprise you.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">2</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Restraint specification</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">Seven refusal categories - sovereignty, scope, safety, authority, uncertainty, privacy, consent - with fail-closed and fail-open decisions for each.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">3</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Accountability architecture</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">Decision logging, human-in-the-loop gates, rollback capability, incident response. When a refusal fires - who is notified, who reviews, who can override.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">4</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Adversarial testing</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">Six scenarios designed to break your specification - the reasonable request, the authority override, the incremental escalation. Find the gaps here, not in the wild.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · IV" heading="Who this is for">
    <div class="pd-audience">
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Builders shipping agents</h3>
        <p>You built the capability. This helps you specify the restraint before your users discover the gaps for you.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Security teams</h3>
        <p>Agent capability gaps are attack surfaces. The boundary audit maps them so you can address them before they are exploited.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Solo developers</h3>
        <p>A solo developer with a written restraint specification is more prepared than most enterprise teams. Dedicated section included for teams of one.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · V" heading="Buy the template">
    <div class="pd-purchase">
      <div class="pd-price">$49</div>
      <p class="pd-purchase-lead">One template. Define the boundaries your agents are missing.</p>
      <a
        href={product.stripePaymentLink}
        class="pd-buy-cta"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >Get the Template</a>
      <p class="pd-purchase-fineprint">
        Boundary audit, refusal category matrix, fail-mode framework,
        accountability architecture, adversarial testing checklist, and solo
        developer adaptation guide.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="NOTA · BENE" heading="Go deeper" closing={true}>
    <p class="lede">
      The template gives you the restraint specification. If you want the full
      trust architecture around it, two doorways from here.
    </p>
    <div class="pd-upsell">
      <a href="/products/trust-architecture-complete" class="pd-upsell-card">
        <h3>The complete bundle</h3>
        <p>All four trust architecture products - Blueprint, Voice, Governance, and Restraint - for $149. Save $47.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">See the bundle &rarr;</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://cal.com/cal.com-evoked/discovery-call" class="pd-upsell-card" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <h3>Discovery call</h3>
        <p>Free 30-minute call to discuss your restraint architecture and figure out next steps.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">Schedule &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>

<style>
  /* Page-local: 4-question self-assessment block.
     If 2-3 more product pages adopt this pattern (governance-score-card
     and the Level 6 instruments are likely candidates), promote
     .pd-checks to elevation.css. */
  .pd-checks {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    margin: clamp(1.5rem, 1rem + 1.5vw, 2.5rem) 0 clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 0.75vw, 1.75rem);
    border: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
  }
  .pd-check {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: clamp(1rem, 0.75rem + 1vw, 1.5rem);
    padding: clamp(1rem, 0.85rem + 0.6vw, 1.5rem) clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 0.75vw, 1.75rem);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
  }
  .pd-check:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .pd-check-number {
    font-family: var(--el-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 0.75vw, 1.6rem);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    line-height: 1;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 1.75rem;
    text-align: center;
    padding-top: 2px;
  }
  .pd-check-body { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }
  .pd-check-question {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: clamp(0.95rem, 0.9rem + 0.25vw, 1.05rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--el-text);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .pd-check-result {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: clamp(0.85rem, 0.8rem + 0.2vw, 0.95rem);
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--el-text-soft);
    margin: 0;
  }
  @media (max-width: 480px) {
    .pd-check { flex-direction: column; align-items: flex-start; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .pd-check-number { width: auto; text-align: left; padding-top: 0; }
  }
</style>
